Date: Mon, 1 Dec 1997 14:37:59 -0500
From: "Schantz, Peter M." <pms1@cdc.gov>

I would like to point out a minor but important error in the 24 November
ProMed-mail message [first reference cited above.
The cestode agent whose prevalence has increased in Germany and elsewhere
in Europe, with potential important public health implications, is
_Echinococcus multilocularis_, not _E. granulosus_ as stated. The latter
primarily cycles in domestic dogs and sheep and other livestock species.
_E. multilocularis_ occurs in life cycles involving foxes and their rodent
prey and the disease it causes in humans, alveolar echinococcosis, is a
serious and potentially fatal malignant-type mass lesion affecting the
liver and other organs.
The increase of this disease in Germany has been temporally associated with
the increase in the fox host density, however, interpretation of the
numbers of human cases is complicated by increased awareness and improved
diagnosis.
--
